         <abstract>
            <p>The author presents a generalization he worked out in 1950 of von Neumann's method of generating random samples from the exponential distribution by comparisons of uniform random numbers on $(0, 1)$. It is shown how to generate samples from any distribution whose probability density function is piecewise both absolutely continuous and monotonic on $(-\infty, \infty)$. A special case delivers normal deviates at an average cost of only 4.036 uniform deviates each. This seems more efficient than the Center-Tail method of Dieter and Ahrens, which uses a related, but different, method of generalizing the von Neumann idea to the normal distribution.</p>
          </abstract>
